n and Suspicion in UK ESOL Policy -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is the fruition of five years’ work in exploring the idea of superdiversity. The editors argue that sociolinguistic superdiversity could be a source of inspiration to a wide range of post-structuralist, post-colonial and neo-Marxist interdisciplinary research into the potential and the limits of human cultural creativity and societal renewal under conditions of increasing and complexifying global connectivity. Through case studies of language practices in spaces understood as inherently translocal and multi-layered (classrooms and schools, youth spaces, mercantile spaces and nation-states), this book explores the relevance of superdiversity for the social and human sciences and positions it as a research perspective in sociolinguistics and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagexVariation. 0aLanguages in contact. 0aMultilingualismxSocial aspects. 0aSociolinguistics. 0aSpace and time in language. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh  aEnregisterment.  aImmigration.  aInfrastructures.  aLanguage Practices.  aMultilingualism.  aPost-colonial.  aSociolinguistics.  aSuperdiversity.  aTransnationalism.1 aArnaut, Karel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnaut, Karel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlommaert, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlommaert, Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoebel, Zane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarrebæk, Martha Sif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat